{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20971"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20971"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0,0.03,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43737"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening right knee pain. She reports difficulty with walking, climbing stairs, and getting up from a chair. The pain is worse with activity and improves with rest. She has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. She is retired and lives with her husband in a two-storey home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m\u00b2. Examination of her right knee reveals mild swelling, crepitus on movement, and tenderness along the medial joint line. Range of motion is limited by pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to provide sustained improvement in this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Knee joint aspiration and steroid injection","Daily hot bath immersion","Regular sauna sessions","Transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation","Supervised aquatic exercise program"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms and signs of knee osteoarthritis (OA). Management of OA involves a multimodal approach including non-pharmacological and pharmacological interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupervised aquatic exercise program\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option for sustained improvement in this patient\u0027s symptoms, based on NHMRC level I evidence. Aquatic exercise performed in warm water (32-36\u00b0C) has been shown to reduce pain and disability while increasing quality of life in patients with knee or hip OA. These benefits occur through increased muscle strength, balance, coordination and joint mobility. Evidence shows that compared to control groups, participants who engaged in aquatic exercise demonstrated a 5-point lower mean pain and disability on a 0-100 scale, and a 7-point higher mean quality of life. The recommended regimen is 2-3 sessions per week of 30-60 minutes each, for approximately 12 weeks. Aquatic exercise is particularly beneficial as initial therapy because water buoyancy reduces load on weight-bearing joints, water resistance helps strengthen muscles, and warm water can reduce pain sensation and stiffness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily hot bath immersion\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide the same benefits as active aquatic exercise. Passive aquatic treatment such as spa or hot bath immersion may provide temporary relief but does not produce the sustained improvements seen with active exercise in water. Without the active component of exercise, the patient would not gain the muscle strengthening, balance, and coordination benefits that contribute to long-term symptom improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular sauna sessions\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary pain relief through heat therapy and muscle relaxation, but like hot bath immersion, this is a passive intervention. While heat can temporarily reduce pain and stiffness, sauna sessions do not address the underlying muscle weakness, joint instability, or functional limitations associated with knee OA. Without an active exercise component, sauna therapy alone would not provide sustained improvement in symptoms or function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscutaneous electrical nerve stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E (TENS) provides short-term pain relief through electrical stimulation of sensory nerves. It may be useful as an adjunctive therapy for pain management in the short-term, rather than long-term use for sustained benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKnee joint aspiration and steroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E can provide short-term pain relief for knee OA. However, this is not a strategy that will likely lead to sustained improvement. This approach may be more appropriate for acute flares of pain rather than as a primary management strategy for long-term symptom control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aquatic exercise is effective for reducing pain and disability in patients with osteoarthritis of the knee or hip.","Aquatic exercise provides benefits through increased muscle strength, balance, coordination and joint mobility.","Water buoyancy reduces load on weight-bearing joints while water resistance helps strengthen muscles."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Aquatic exercise for knee and hip osteoarthritis. Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/a/aquatic-exercise-for-knee-and-hip-osteoarthritis","RACGP Guidelines for the non-surgical management of hip and knee osteoarthritis. 2009. Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/knee-and-hip-osteoarthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20971"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83408"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-29T09:06:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-29T09:06:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"